    pearls: ["Uhthoff's phenomenon: symptoms worsen with heat but this is NOT a relapse", "Lhermitte's sign is highly suggestive of cervical cord demyelination", "Fatigue is the most disabling symptom for many patients: teach energy conservation", "UTI and other infections can trigger pseudo-relapses: treat the infection first"],
    lifespan: { title: "Across the Lifespan", content: "Pediatric MS (onset before 18) accounts for 3-5% of cases and tends to have more inflammatory relapses but better recovery. Late-onset MS (after 50) is more likely to be progressive from onset." },
    quiz: [{ question: "A patient with MS reports that their vision becomes blurry after taking a hot shower but returns to normal after cooling down. What should the nurse teach?", options: ["This indicates a new relapse requiring IV steroids", "This is Uhthoff's phenomenon: avoid overheating but it is not a true relapse", "The patient should stop all disease-modifying therapy", "This requires emergent MRI to evaluate for new lesions"], correct: 1, rationale: "Uhthoff's phenomenon is the temporary worsening of MS symptoms with elevated body temperature. Heat slows conduction in demyelinated nerve fibers. It is NOT a true relapse and does not indicate new disease activity. The nurse should teach strategies to stay cool." }]
